## Incident Resolution Summary

### Root Cause
The `orders` table (500M rows) had **only a primary key index on `id`**. Any query filtering by `user_id`, `order_date`, or `status` was performing a full sequential scan across 500 million rows — hence the 10+ second response times and millions of slow query incidents.

### Actions Taken

Created three B-Tree indexes using `CREATE INDEX CONCURRENTLY` (per the operational guide) to avoid blocking the 24/7 write traffic:

| Index | Column | Lock Type | Writes Blocked? |
|---|---|---|---|
| `idx_orders_user_id` | `user_id` | ShareUpdateExclusiveLock | ❌ No |
| `idx_orders_order_date` | `order_date` | ShareUpdateExclusiveLock | ❌ No |
| `idx_orders_status` | `status` | ShareUpdateExclusiveLock | ❌ No |

### Key Safety Measures
- **`CONCURRENTLY`** used for all index builds — no table-level write locks, no order operation disruption
- Each statement executed outside a transaction block (as required for concurrent index builds)
- Verified all indexes exist and no residual locks remain

### Expected Impact
Queries on `user_id`, `order_date`, and `status` will now use index scans instead of sequential scans, bringing response times from 10+ seconds down to milliseconds. Dashboard metrics should normalize shortly as the query planner picks up the new indexes.
